            <h2 class="my-1 text-2xl font-semibold">Area of Interest:</h2>
            <p>I am interested in... <span class="font-semibold">Software Development, Web Development, Linux.</span></p><br>
            <ul class="list-disc">
                <li><span class="font-semibold">Software Development:</span> I have been using all kinds of software since a young age. From simple calculators to AAA videogames, all have piqued my interest. It's thanks to this lifetime exposure to software that I eventually ended up making my own. It started with calculators and eventually ended up with screen recorders and web browsers. I have a keen interest in the inner workings of software and happily spend my free time tinkering around with new languages and frameworks, seeing where might I end up today. <span class="italic font-semibold">[Specific area of interest: creating CLI tools using Go]</span></li><br>
                <li><span class="font-semibold">Web Development:</span> I like making software that is accessible to all kinds of people, on all kinds of devices. I generally enjoy Web Development the most in my day-to-day activities. Making solid back-ends using PHP and Shellscript, all the while making pretty and comfortable front-ends using Tailwind and JS makes me consider things I normally wouldn't think about. UX/UI design, cross-compatibility for smaller devices such as mobile, tablet, but also larger devices such as 4K monitors and 8K televisions & the large amount of frameworks and tools to tinker with make Web Development the perfect playground for any developer - including me. <span class="font-semibold italic">[Specific area of interest: back-end using PHP]</span></li><br>
                <li><span class="font-semibold">Linux:</span> My strongest interest lies in web back-end development. Thanks to this interest I use Linux frequently - everyday in fact. I run Linux on all of my servers (RPI cloud server, VPS webserver) and my personal desktop and laptop. It is my preferred work environment for all my day-to-day tasks. I don't know what specifically grasps me, it could be the terminal usage with the amazingly well-designed GNU commands, or it could be the customizability of a desktop environment such as GNOME or even a window manager such as i3. It could be the well-thought-out Linux workflow with redirects and pipelines, cronjobs and Vim galore. While I don't know what specifically has me coming back to this kind of environment everyday, I do know that it's something that I am most efficient at. <span class="font-semibold italic">[Specific area of interest: configuring cron, webserver and development environments using the terminal]</span></li>
            </ul>
